Now I can see the problem! Looking at the `retainAll` method in the `ListOrderedSet` class, I can see that the current implementation has an inefficient algorithm. Here's the problematic section:

```java
@Override
public boolean retainAll(Collection<?> coll) {
    boolean result = collection.retainAll(coll);
    if (result == false) {
        return false;
    }
    if (collection.size() == 0) {
        setOrder.clear();
    } else {
        for (Iterator<E> it = setOrder.iterator(); it.hasNext();) {
            if (!collection.contains(it.next())) {
                it.remove();
            }
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

The issue is in the else block. For each element in `setOrder`, the code calls `collection.contains()` which can be O(n) for each lookup. For a large set (100,000 elements), this becomes O(n²) complexity, causing the timeout in the test.

The fix should be to replace the linear scanning with a more efficient approach. Instead of calling `collection.contains()` repeatedly, we should rebuild the `setOrder` list by iterating through it once and keeping only elements that are present in the collection.

